The term "'''big ticket item'''" is [[North America|North American]] [[slang]] used to refer to high end luxury items. 

Although most people would use the term in regards to an item of significant physical size, like a computer or a sports car or big screen TV, the term can be applied to just about any expensive item (Jewelry, sound systems, expensive suits, etc.)

The term itself is derived partially from the idea that the price is high (Big) and partially from the idea that larger products have physically larger price tags (Big tickets).

Some items are constant big ticket items, such as jewelry and state of the art TVs, others may fall out of the category after an initial rush at introduction. For example, the [[Tickle Me Elmo]] doll was the "big ticket item" of the 1996 Holiday shopping season.

